]1. Creating REST Controllers with @RestController

Theory:
@RestController is a Spring annotation that marks a class as a REST controller.
It combines @Controller and @ResponseBody, so every method returns data (like JSON) directly,
not a view (like HTML).

Implementation:

@RestController
public class UserController {
    // Methods here will return JSON by default
}

2. Mapping URLs with @RequestMapping, @GetMapping, @PostMapping, etc.

Theory:
You use these annotations to connect HTTP requests (like GET, POST) to Java methods.
@RequestMapping is general; @GetMapping, @PostMapping, @PutMapping, and @DeleteMapping are
shortcuts for specific HTTP methods.

Implementation:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users") // Base URL for all methods in this controller
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping // Handles GET /users
    public List<User> getAllUsers() { ... }

    @GetMapping("/{id}") // Handles GET /users/123
    public User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }

    @PostMapping // Handles POST /users
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) { ... }

    @PutMapping("/{id}") // Handles PUT /users/123
    public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) { ... }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}") // Handles DELETE /users/123
    public void deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }
}

3. Handling Request Parameters with @RequestParam and @PathVariable

Theory:
@RequestParam gets query parameters from the URL (like ?name=Alice).
@PathVariable gets values from the URL path (like /users/123).

Implementation:

// Example: GET /users/search?name=Alice
@GetMapping("/search")
public List<User> searchUsers(@RequestParam String name) {
    // 'name' comes from the query parameter
    return userService.findByName(name);
}

// Example: GET /users/123
@GetMapping("/{id}")
public User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
    // 'id' comes from the URL path
    return userService.findById(id);
}

4. Accepting JSON Data with @RequestBody

Theory:
@RequestBody tells Spring to convert incoming JSON into a Java object.
Used for POST and PUT requests, where the client sends data.

Implementation:

Ex:

// Example: POST /users with JSON body
@PostMapping
public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
    // 'user' is automatically populated from the JSON request body
    return userService.save(user);
}

// Example: PUT /users/123 with JSON body
@PutMapping("/{id}")
public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
    // 'user' is populated from JSON, 'id' from URL
    return userService.update(id, user);
}

5. Summary Table

Annotation	               Purpose	                               Example Usage

@RestController	           Marks class as REST controller	       @RestController
@RequestMapping	           Maps URL to method (any HTTP method)	   @RequestMapping("/users")
@GetMapping	               Maps GET requests	                   @GetMapping("/{id}")
@PostMapping	           Maps POST requests	                   @PostMapping
@PutMapping	               Maps PUT requests	                   @PutMapping("/{id}")
@DeleteMapping	           Maps DELETE requests	                   @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
@RequestParam	           Gets query parameter from URL	       @RequestParam String name
@PathVariable	           Gets value from URL path	               @PathVariable Long id
@RequestBody	           Gets JSON from request body	           @RequestBody User user